<SAGPLayout title="2023 Distinguished Lectureship | SAGP">

<section class="hero">
  <div class="hero-inner">
    <div class="kicker">2023 Distinguished Lectureship</div>
    <h1>Tony Long</h1>
    <p class="lede">“The Stoic Zeus and the Values of Nature”</p>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section two-col">
  <div><h2>The 2023 lecture</h2></div>
  <div>
    <p><strong>Tony Long</strong>, Chancellor’s Distinguished Professor Emeritus of Classics and Affiliated Professor of Philosophy, University of California, Berkeley.</p>
    <p><strong>Date:</strong> Tuesday, March 12, 2024 · 12:00pm Eastern.</p>
    <p><strong>Commentators:</strong> Tad Brennan and Gretchen Reydams-Schils.</p>
    <p>This lecture was rescheduled from 2023 and held via Zoom.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section two-col">
  <div><h2>Abstract</h2></div>
  <div>
    <p>
      The founders of Stoicism applied a range of terms to the world’s active principle,
      including god, nature, cause, reason, fate, and necessity.
    </p>
    <p>
      Long examines the conceptual relationship between these designations, especially
      that between nature and Zeus, and considers Chrysippus’s claim that Zeus and
      universal nature are the foundation of justice and ethical theory.
    </p>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section two-col">
  <div><h2>Participants</h2></div>
  <div>
    <p>
      Tony Long’s publications range from the Presocratics to Plotinus, with special
      focus on Hellenistic philosophy.
    </p>
    <p>
      Tad Brennan is Professor of Philosophy and Classics at Cornell University.
    </p>
    <p>
      Gretchen Reydams-Schils is Professor in the Program of Liberal Studies at the University of Notre Dame.
    </p>
  </div>
</section>

